Dear Mrs. Langley was not particularly happy about her job. She owned alakeside bungalow ("Rustic Roses") thirty miles north of Quirn, not very farfrom Honeywell College, where she taught summer school and with which sheintended to be even more closely associated, if a "reactionary" atmospherepersisted at Quirn. Actually, her only grudge was against decrepit Mme. deKorchakov, who had accused he